body:
Apologies for the nonspecific issue title, I'm not sure what's the root cause of the bug. I have this code:

``` verilog
module top(
        (* LOC="P4"  *) output coilA1,
        (* LOC="P6"  *) output coilA2,
        (* LOC="P8"  *) output coilB1,
        (* LOC="P10" *) output coilB2
    );

    wire strobe;
    GP_LFOSC #(
        .OUT_DIV(8'd16),
        .AUTO_PWRDN(1'b0)
    ) lfosc (
        .CLKOUT(strobe)
    );

    localparam STATE0 = 4'b0100,
               STATE1 = 4'b0001,
               STATE2 = 4'b1000,
               STATE3 = 4'b0010;
    // (* fsm_encoding="auto" *)
    reg [3:0] state;
    always @(posedge strobe)
        case(state)
            STATE0:  state <= STATE1;
            STATE1:  state <= STATE2;
            STATE2:  state <= STATE3;
            STATE3:  state <= STATE0;
            default: state <= STATE0;
        endcase

    assign {coilA1, coilA2, coilB1, coilB2} = state;

endmodule
```

It works, but translates into lots of LUTs. If I uncomment the fsm_encoding attribute, it is translated into four DFFs, which is what I want, but it doesn't work (all outputs are low) anymore because all of them are initialized to 0. If I explicitly initialize it to `STATE0` (and comment out the `default` case), then it is translated into eight DFFs, and, most interestingly, still doesn't work (all outputs stay low), despite one of the DFFs being initialized to 1.

I'm synthesizing using `yosys -p "synth_greenpak4 -part SLG46620V -json test.txt" test.v`, using commit e42041204.

I'm not sure what should happen according to the standard in the case where `reg` is uninitialized (though @azonenberg thinks it ought be the same as without the FSM annotation), but the second case seems clearly wrong.
